Beyond the forecast injection for the week in progress, decidedly more shoulder season injections are on the horizon as cooling load dissipates both seasonally and on current weather forecasts

- Vinci has released its July traffic report for toll roads and airports, following market close.

- For Autoroutes, Vinci reported a \(+1\%\) increase y/y (vs \(+2.3\%\) in Q2). The growth was driven by Light Vehicle (LV) traffic at \(+1\%\) y/y in July (vs \(+2.7\%\) in Q2), while Heavy vehicles (HV) were \(+0.4\%\) y/y (vs \(-0.4\%\) in Q2). Overall, YTD, traffic levels have risen by \(2.2\%\) for LV, \(0.5\%\) for HV and \(2\%\) for total traffic.

- In the airport sector, Vinci reported continuous positive trends in July at \(+3.6\%\) y/y (vs \(+5.1\%\) in June). Traffic at ANA stood at \(+5.2\%\) y/y (vs \(+5.9\%\) in June). Similarly, OMA saw positive y/y trends with \(7.7\%\) growth (vs \(+9.2\%\) in June), while traffic in France was up \(1.6\%\) y/y (vs \(+2.4\%\) in June). UK traffic stood at \(+0.3\%\) y/y (-0.2\%\) in June). The US experienced a decline in traffic at \(-10\%\) y/y (vs \(-8.1\%\) in June)
- July Autoroutes traffic of \(+1\%\) increase y/y compares to \(+2.3\%\) in Q2) whilst July Airport traffic growth continued to slow sequentially this year, as guided by the company

- We update our model following Eiffage's H1 results (link to our first take). Our 25E EBIT decreases slightly as we increase our estimate for the Holding level loss, with our Contracting EBIT increasing and Concessions EBIT very slightly decreasing. We also incorporate revised guidance for the impact of France's surtax in 2025, underpinning the increase in our 25E Net Income. 
- Our Dec-26 PT is unchanged at €136, now implying \(25\%\) upside to the current share price, despite our increased estimates as we MTM in our WACC for interest rates

- Today's EIA print once more came in below market expectations, which called for a build in the high 20s Bcf but was relatively in line with our supply-demand forecast calling for a 21 Bcf injection. Our lower-than-consensus estimate was driven by power burns that were trending above 49 Bcf/day for the reference week, according to EIA 930 data (Figure 1). We believe today's and last week's EIA print corroborate strong weather-aided demand with estimated gas power burn above 49 Bcf/day for the reference week and the week ending August 15. Based on forecasts as of this morning, August gas power burn looks on track to average just above 46 Bcf/d, which still represents a \(\sim 2\) Bcf/day year-over-year decline.

- Our preliminary storage injection estimate for the week ending August 22 is 51 Bcf. Daily gas power burn appears to be on track to fall nearly 5 Bcf/day week-over-week, and this decline is the main driver of that substantially higher injection rate (Figure 1). We also note that EIA 930 data point to lower week-over-week coal-fired power generation more in line with levels last seen in May and June (Figure 2). Pipeline data suggest that production is up week-over-week, and we have built in a 0.6 Bcf/day week-over-week increase versus the reference week. The Pacific region storage sample is showing a higher week-over-week withdrawal compared to the reference week. EIA 930 data for CAISO through yesterday show a 1 Bcf/day increase week-over-week in power burn for the region. Beyond the forecast injection for the week in progress, decidedly more shoulder season injections are on the horizon as cooling load dissipates both seasonally and on current weather forecasts

- Renewables Now reported that Potentia Energy, a joint venture between Italy's Enel Green Power and Japanese oil group Inpex Corp, has secured environmental approval for a 225-MW/900-MWh battery project in South Australia.
- The Emeroo energy storage scheme is the first one to be granted environmental permit under South Australia's Hydrogen and Renewable Energy (HRE) Act, Potentia Energy said on Wednesday.

- The legislation came into effect last summer to create a "one-window" licensing and regulatory framework for hydrogen, renewable energy, and energy storage. Calling for an investment of AUD 400 million (USD 260.3m/EUR 223.7m), the Emeroo battery energy storage system (BESS) will be able to provide up to four hours of storage capacity.

- With the enviro permit in place, project development for Emeroo will advance towards final approvals and a final investment decision. Potentia Energy expects to start building works next year and bring the BESS online in 2028. In South Australia, Potentia Energy said it is also developing the 125-MW Blanche and 270-MW Harrogate battery projects.

- Enel continues to do a good job in delivering organic and inorganic growth in renewables in Australia, with expectations for low to mid 100MWs in renewables additions over the next couple of years, though we won't see this in in EBITDA given the structure is a 50:50 JV

- Renewables Now reported that RWE has commissioned a 12-MWac/13.9-MWp solar photovoltaic plant on the edge of the Hambach opencast mine in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia, adding another completed project to its renewables portfolio in the Rhenish region. Built in less than five months, the solar farm near Niederzier covers about 12 hectares and comprises more than 22,000 panels, capable of supplying around 4,500 households with power, the company said. An artificial intelligence tool was used during construction to monitor progress with drone imagery and detect deviations from plans.

- The new facility is RWE's third solar project at the Hambach site, where it already operates two plants with a combined 47.2 MW capacity and an 8-MWh battery storage system in partnership with local inter-municipal consortium NEULAND

HAMBACH. The municipalities represented by the organisation have the option to take a share in the new solar farm as well. RWE said it now runs eight solar farms in the Rhenish region, four of them combined with storage, alongside nine onshore wind farms. Additional projects are under construction or in planning.

Markets - SPX was up 30bps from the European close to finish \(0.32\%\) higher on the day (6,502). It was a risk on session with cyclicals outperforming defensives by almost \(2\%\) . Momentum L/S 12m recovered yesterday loss finishing up \(1.94\%\) with TMT Crowded Longs up more than \(2.50\%\) . Overall volumes tracked \(14\%\) below the 30 dma as treasury yields and USD sold off with Oil moving higher. Communication services and energy were the best sectors with utilities and staples the worst. JPM cash was slightly better to buy with financials and healthcare leading the skew. Tech and consumer discretionary were better for sale. After the close Dell \(- 5\%\) . The press is looking at this weekend energy summit in China between Putin, Xi and Modi and France political situation. Overnight USD and treasuries have remained mainly flat and commodities are lower. Today in US we have PCE, Consumer Spending and UMich Consumer Sentiment. In Europe we have ECB CPI Expectations and Germany, France, Italy and Spain CPI. Asia markets are higher with the exception of Japan and Korea. JPM cash volumes are \(+10\%\) vs 5dma and we are \(1.5x\) better to buy. We are buying in China, Japan, Korea and Indonesia vs selling in Australia, HK, Taiwan and Singapore. In the sectors we are buying industrials, consumer discretionary and materials versus selling tech and financials.
